"begin": 1214, "end": 1217}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9796739220619202, "span": {"begin": 1227, "end": 1231}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009630"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "non", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8407919406890869, "span": {"begin": 1260, "end": 1263}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9743101596832275, "span": {"begin": 1270, "end": 1274}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:207"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Akt", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9843766689300537, "span": {"begin": 1355, "end": 1358}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9813054203987122, "span": {"begin": 1363, "end": 1367}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "VEGF-stimulated HUVECs", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.7973751425743103, "span": {"begin": 1371, "end": 1393}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7422"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "VEGF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9734773635864258, "span": {"begin": 1371, "end": 1375}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HUVECs", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9563198089599609, "span": {"begin": 1387, "end": 1393}}, {"id": ["mesh:D017202"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Myocardial ischemia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9812435507774353, "span": {"begin": 1418, "end": 1437}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:207"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AKT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9871227741241455, "span": {"begin": 1463, "end": 1466}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9896536469459534, "span": {"begin": 1471, "end": 1475}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006973"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "spontaneously hypertension", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9983357191085815, "span": {"begin": 1479, "end": 1505}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rats", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.4818418323993683, "span": {"begin": 1512, "end": 1516}}], "text": "Multiple experimental studies reported modulations in Akt and eNOS phosphorylation/activity following oxidative stress, thus providing strong biological plausibility for this key event relationship.  In HUVECs, peroxynitrite significantly inhibited AKT&nbsp;phosphorylation at Ser473 and AKT&nbsp;activity (Song et al., 2007, 2008; Zou et al., 2002). However, Zou et al. (2002) found that peroxynitrite increased eNOS phosphorylation at Ser1199, but decreased NO availability, suggesting eNOS phosphorylation may not depend on AKT. Treatment of BAECs with SIN-1, a source of peroxynitrite, inhibited eNOS activity by 30% and AKT/eNOS phosphorylation (Das et al., 2014).  High glucose concentrations can also inhibit AKT&nbsp;phosphorylation (Song et al., 2008). HUVECs treated with methylglyoxal and high concentrations of glucose exhibited reduced bradykinin-stimulated eNOS activity via Ser1177 phosphorylation (Dhar et al., 2010), while hyperglycemia inhibited eNOS activity in BAECs (Du et al., 2001). In EA.hy926 endothelial cells, methylglyoxal treatment results in reduced eNOS phosphorylation at Ser1177 (Su et al., 2013). High-fat diet-induced obesity in mice caused an increase in ROS and a reduction in AKT&nbsp;and eNOS phosphorylation compared to non-obese mice (Du et al., 2013).  Treatment with cigarette smoke extract (CSE) also inhibited Akt and eNOS in VEGF-stimulated HUVECs (Michaud et al., 2006). Myocardial ischemia decreased phosphorylated AKT and eNOS in spontaneously hypertension (SHR) rats compared to sham animals (Zhang et al., 2014).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:53:24 +0000 2026"}